<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a saw kerf?", answer: "A saw kerf is the width of material removed by the blade as it cuts. Every time a blade passes through wood, it turns a thin strip of material into sawdust. For a table saw, the kerf is typically 1/8 inch (0.125) for a standard full-kerf blade or 3/32 inch (0.094) for a thin-kerf blade. Kerf width must be accounted for when planning rip cuts so that the finished strips actually fit across the width of the board." },
  { question: "How do I measure my blade's kerf?", answer: "The easiest way to measure kerf is to check the manufacturer's specifications, which are usually printed on the blade itself or in its product listing. You can also measure it directly with digital calipers by placing the jaws against the widest part of two adjacent carbide teeth. Typical values are 0.094 inches for thin-kerf blades, 0.125 inches for standard full-kerf blades, and 0.156 inches for heavy-duty full-kerf blades." },
  { question: "Does a thinner kerf save much wood?", answer: "Over a single rip cut the savings are tiny, but across a project with many strips the difference adds up. A thin-kerf blade removes about 25 percent less material per cut than a standard full-kerf blade. On a 24 inch board ripped into 1 inch strips, the thin-kerf blade leaves enough extra material for roughly one additional strip compared to a thicker blade." },
  { question: "Why account for kerf when planning rips?", answer: "Ignoring kerf leads to cut lists that do not fit. If you plan to rip a 12 inch board into four 3 inch strips without accounting for kerf, the three kerf cuts between them remove another 3/8 inch, and your last strip will end up 3/8 inch undersized. Always subtract the kerf from the usable width or use a calculator that handles it for you." },
  { question: "Can I use this for crosscuts?", answer: "Yes. The math is identical for any series of parallel cuts on a board, whether you are ripping along the grain or crosscutting across it. Just enter your board length in place of the width, and the strip length you want in place of the rip width. The calculator will tell you how many pieces you can get and how much material is lost to the saw blade." }
]) %>

